Package org.graphstream.algorithm.generator Description

Various graph generators with specific properties.

Graph generators are classes that can be used as iterators, but instead of iterating on already existing elements, they create them on the fly. Often the more one iterates on the generator, the larger the graph becomes. Some generator are finite, whereas others are not.

Generators have very few methods (apart from the generation parameter setup methods that are specific to each generator). They are:

  • Generator.begin() to start the generation of elements in the given graph. This graph may or not already contain elements.
  • Generator.nextEvents() to generate one or a set of elements in the graph. The more this method is iterated, the more the graph grows. This method returns false when no more elements can be generated. BE CAREFUL: some generators never return false: they can generate graphs of arbitrary size.
  • Generator.end() to finish the graph generation process, either once Generator.nextEvents() returned false, or one chooses to stop the generation process.
